article.headline: Lady Vols clinch sixth straight SEC regular-season title
article.linkText: Lady Vols celebrate Senior Night by clinching sixth straight SEC title
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Because Kara Lawson's parents were going to be late for senior night, Tennessee decided to hold the festivities after the game.

Lawson and fellow senior Gwen Jackson had other plans.

They did their celebrating during the game as the No. 3 Lady Vols beat Vanderbilt (No. 18 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) 91-71 Thursday night to clinch the Southeastern Conference regular-season title for the sixth straight season.

Lawson, whose parents arrived a little before halftime after two
of their flights from Washington, D.C. were canceled, scored a
career-high 31 points and made all six 3-pointers she attempted.

"She seemed to be a whole different person and played with a
lot of inspiration. Very aggressive from the three-point line and
just hustle plays and rebounds,'' Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said.
"That's the Kara Lawson that we need from here on out.''

Jackson added 19 points, reserve Shanna Zolman had 16 and Shyra
Ely 14 points for Tennessee, who put the game away with a 16-0 run
late in the second half.

The Commodores (18-8, 8-5) were led by Chantelle Anderson, who
scored a season-high 35 points. Anderson dislocated her right toe
in Vanderbilt's 81-67 loss to Tennessee on Feb. 2 and scored 21
points in that game.

Abi Ramsey was 6-of-9 from behind the 3-point line, finishing
with a career-high 20 points for Vanderbilt, which is 0-18 in
Knoxville and has lost four straight to Tennessee.

"Our goal from the beginning of the year was to win the regular-season title, and Coach told us before the game we had the opportunity to win it outright,'' Lawson said. "It was a big game for us.''

Tennessee led nearly the entire game, but Vanderbilt was able to
stay close because of Anderson's inside presence and Ramsey's
outside shooting.

   The Commodores pulled within nine with 7:21 to go after a basket
by Anderson, but they could not get closer. The Lady Vols then put
the game away with their decisive run over the next three minutes.

Jackson scored two baskets, Lawson hit a 3, Zolman scored twice
and Brittany Jackson had four free throws as Tennessee went ahead
84-59 with 4:11 left.

   Anderson ended Vanderbilt's drought with a pair of free throws,
but it was too late for a rally.

   "They went on a run. They shot 70 percent (in the second half)
and got hot. We didn't get back in transition and didn't get any
stops,'' Vanderbilt coach Melanie Balcomb said. "As the game wore
on, mentally it is demoralizing when you can't score and that
affects your defense.''

Summitt presented flowers to Anderson and Ashley McElhiney, the Vanderbilt seniors who have played well against Tennessee during their careers.

"It was cool. I didn't expect it,'' Anderson said.

   When asked if she was going to miss playing Tennessee, Anderson
replied sarcastically: "Right.''

"That was a no,'' she then added.

Tennessee's two seniors, Lawson and Jackson, stepped up in their
final regular-season game.

   Lawson was 9-of-12 from the field and made all seven free throws
she attempted. She shook her head after scoring a 3 and flexed her
arms like a bodybuilder after the Lady Vols were ahead for good.

After the game, the two seniors were honored with their families
and then each addressed the crowd.

"Speaking of coach Summitt, she taught me a lot about working
hard. As a freshman I never thought I'd play the way I am now.
Somehow she got it out of me,'' Jackson said.

"That was a heck of a game, wasn't it?'' Lawson said. "It's
like Gwen said, it's been a great four years!''

Tennessee led 35-32 at halftime before Lawson hit two 3-pointers
and Jackson scored five points early in the second half as the Lady
Vols went ahead by eight.

Ramsey hit back-to-back 3-pointers for Vanderbilt, Zolman hit a
3 and Lawson had a driving layup to put Tennessee ahead by 10 with
15:38 remaining.

   Anderson scored Vanderbilt's first 14 points of the game and had
18 by halftime. No other Commodore scored until Ramsey's 3-pointer
with 7:43 remaining in the first half.

"When you assess the frontline people that we face, she has been one of the best with establishing and having her way on the block,'' Summitt said.

Anderson's presence was frustrating the Lady Vols during the first half. Ely tried to grab an offensive rebound from Anderson under the Tennessee basket but lost it and shoved Anderson with her forearm. Ely was called for a technical foul.
